<p>This article is an analysis of British expeditionary capability as seen through the eyes of the United States Army Training and Doctrine Command (TRADOC) Liaison Officer to the British Army's Land Warfare Center (referred to as US LO) while accompanying the British Development, Concepts, and Doctrine Centre (DCDC) staff on its battlefield study of Operating at Range (Expeditionary Operations). DCDC conducted this study through the lens of Operation Corporate, the British operation to liberate the Falkland Islands in 1982.</p>
<p>The study consisted of historical analysis of Operation Corporate and contemporary analysis of current British capability to project expeditionary power in general and in the Atlantic specifically. The DCDC team used the staff ride format to visit Ascension Island in the central Atlantic Ocean and the Falkland Islands in the South Atlantic. These locations were instrumental in understanding Operation Corporate and the British military's expeditionary capability. The resulting analysis suggested that current British doctrine for expeditionary operations is well-established and thoroughly capable, but they currently are not funded adequately to execute unilateral expeditionary operations without exposing their forces to significant risk. As a result of funding shortfalls British forces cannot effectively isolate an operational objective in an expeditionary environment, nor can they properly sustain themselves once ashore.</p>
<p>British Military doctrine is currently capable of accurately directing requirements for expeditionary operations, but there appears to be dissonance between British military doctrinal concepts and the availability of assets to enable that doctrine. Study of Operation Corporate and subsequent discussions about current British doctrine illustrated that expeditionary concepts of maneuver, sustainment, and mission command are present and well understood among British leadership. However, the British military does not possess the assets required for operating an expeditionary military force on a unilateral operation where the operation requires forces larger than a battle group and the threat to forces in theater is of such magnitude that those forces could conceivably be destroyed.</p>
<p>In the context of history, Operation Corporate achieved its objectives, but its cost in men and materiel was greater than necessary if British forces had been equipped and sustained to execute the operation as doctrine of the day dictated, even within the constraints of the political objectives. Instead, absolutely heroic efforts were required in 1982 on the parts of all services to isolate the objective, generate combat power ashore, sustain forces in theater, secure those forces, and accomplish the primary mission. Though the British military learned the lessons of Operation Corporate well, and clearly knows what it needs to protect its forces while efficiently accomplishing future expeditionary operations, the availability of assets to support this doctrine remains elusive.</p>
<p>As the British government seeks to support emerging United Nations doctrine and international norms regarding the international responsibility to protect , British military forces are underfunded and under-supported to achieve those policy objectives without subjecting forces to significant risk. Current funding inadequacies require the British military to find doctrinal and operational solutions that place the burden of mission success on personnel and organizational innovation. This was historically apparent in the study of Operation Corporate as sea, air, and ground forces were routinely required to sacrifice casualties, tempo, mass, and maneuver as a result of insufficient availability of materiel intertwined with aggressive military and political objectives.</p>
<p>A lack of readily available capability in the form of materiel and deployable forces leads directly to a practical problem at the operational level for British forces. Doctrine regarding expeditionary operations (employed with operational maneuver as opposed to forced entry) requires that the initial objective be effectively isolated from enemy interference while friendly forces generate sufficient combat power and sustainment capability in the objective area to support follow on operations. British forces currently lack sufficient air and sea assets capable of effectively projecting enough power that a future objective can be properly isolated from a reasonably capable enemy while British forces generate capacity ashore.</p>
