<p>This is not to imply that forces could not be landed and objectives reached, rather it implies that the cost in losses of men and equipment conducting this type of operation would perhaps be prohibitively high. Historically this is demonstrated by Operation Corporate as losses from enemy action up to and during the landing of the landing force totaled eight ships damaged and one sunk, two harriers and six helicopters destroyed, and about 60 personnel killed (dependent on when the landing is considered complete). British capability to isolate an objective at range during 1982 exceeded current conventional capability today. This is most visible through the absence of aircraft carriers and carrier-based aircraft today, but also through the fewer (though more capable) ships available to the Royal Navy (RN), and the absence of intercontinental strategic bombing and reconnaissance capability in the Royal Air Force (RAF). Therefore, there is unlikely to be a less costly outcome for men and equipment under similar conditions in the future.</p>
<p>The second practical problem at the operational level is the insufficient sustainment capability currently available to expeditionary British forces. Current ship to shore movement capability is almost entirely reliant on helicopters and a few (fairly elderly and incapable) landing craft. There is also only a very small capability to extend sustainment over land once in theater. In cases like Operation Corporate the British were forced to rely almost exclusively on helicopter support if not the backs of their soldiers. In modern cases like the British assistance to French forces in Mali, British contingents were forced to employ services like DHL and local businesses to create capability to deliver timely sustainment in necessary quantities.</p>
<p>As in Operation Corporate, current airlift capability does not meet projected sustainment demand, and ship-to-shore and ground-based systems are not capable of moving enough materiel to meet demand (of forces exceeding Battle Group size) without large forward operating bases and coalition help (as in Afghanistan). There is no indication that this will change in the future. In fact, it is likely that the opposite will be true as British forces plan and train to operate almost exclusively inside a US coalition and thus make use of the more robust US sustainment capability.</p>
<p>The lessons of Operation Corporate have been well-heeded by the British military establishment, and current doctrine demonstrates this. British doctrine provides for all generally accepted practices when conducting expeditionary operations or Operations at Range. The shortfall is not doctrinal. The shortfall is in materiel, and thus expeditionary capability. British planning assumes generally that future operations will be conducted within a large coalition almost certainly led by the United States. That assumption must be incorporated into doctrine on both sides of the Atlantic. If the British military is going to rely on the United States for a large proportion of its sustainment and expeditionary capability during future contingency operations, then both sides need to plan and allocate resources for this assumption. U.S. planning assumptions must also include which specific tasks of expeditionary operations will be routinely ceded to the U.S. and then develop sufficient capability for that assumption. British forces are impressive, and anyone who has served with them can attest to their outstanding tactical ability, courage, and leadership, but until military funding reaches levels to enable expeditionary capability to meet doctrinal requirements and ultimately strategic policy goals, the British lion will remain caged on its island waiting for a U.S. coalition to release it.</p>
